overview: "The user initiated a request to fix numerous issues within a pull
  request, emphasizing critical Vercel deployment failures. The agent embarked
  on a comprehensive debugging and fixing process. This involved resolving
  initial linting errors, patching a high-severity admin authentication cookie
  forgery vulnerability by implementing HMAC-based sessions compatible with
  Vercel's Edge Runtime, and addressing data handling issues in API responses
  and CSV exports with pagination and limits. Several bugs related to PDF
  generation (NaN values, minute calculations, hardcoded user names) and number
  input fields were also fixed, alongside adding robust Zod schema validation
  for time inputs. The most challenging aspect involved persistent Vercel
  deployment failures, which required multiple iterations of fixes: first,
  correcting a missing database URL in the Prisma schema; then, upgrading
  Next.js to resolve a critical security vulnerability (CVE-2025-66478), which
  in turn introduced breaking changes in Prisma 7 and Next.js 16's linting
  command, necessitating further configuration adjustments. Finally, a
  build-time error on Vercel related to Prisma client initialization was
  resolved by implementing lazy-loading for the Prisma client. The agent
  demonstrated a methodical approach to identifying and resolving complex,
  interconnected technical issues."
